courses.learning_outcomes:
After taking this course, students are able to:
Acquire the basic knowledge of the history and formation of England;
Analyse the rise of England as world power and how her cultural, institutes and justice system influenced the contemporary world;
Think critically how the industrial revolution changed the ideas such as ‘innovation’ and ‘consumerism’ and how they affected the modern world environment;
Understand how human rights and women rights developed in England;
Integrate SDGs into different historical aspects and how they related to modern world issues.

Guangdong-Hong Kong-Macao Greater Bay Area is a rapidly growing and significant mega-city region in the world. This course will not only offer a broad coverage on various aspects of Hong Kong, Macao and the PRD development, but also place an emphasis on the intricate relationship of the three places. After completing the course, students will be able to:
describe the historical development of Hong Kong, Macao and the PRD;
explain why Hong Kong, Macao and the PRD are closely related and intermingled under the rapid
process of globalization;
use examples to show how a place’s growth and development is associated with regional and global conditions;
relate knowledge to potential employment in the future;
diagnose the social, economic and environmental problems of the region beyond what is presented in the mass media.

Upon completion of the course, students will be able to
1. recognize gender as a fundamental organizing principle of society;
2. describe how gender is constructed and in what ways it influences us at individual, national and global levels;
3. explain gender in various perspectives with sound justifications;
4. theorize cultural issues from a gender perspective
5. reflect upon their life and choices.
6. Consider changes in social practices and policies that can better address gender equality
7. Evaluate the barriers and challenges in achieving gender equality in diverse cultures

By the end of this course, students are expected:
1. ) to acquire knowledge on UN’s sustainable development goals, and to apply their knowledge to critically evaluate the current situations in Hong Kong, Asia and the world;
2. ) to be able to critically evaluate tourism as a means to achieve sustainable cities and communities;
3. ) to be able to scholarly compare Japan to other countries in relation to tourism;
4. ) to reflect on tourism development in Hong Kong.

After taking this course, students will be able to:
explain how cultures function, and recognize the different perspectives that can be used to understand culture;
discuss how different cultures have both diverse and similar solutions to the problems of human existence;
analyze cultures and societies as informed through comparisons with other cultures and societies; and
explicate the connections among different subfields of social and cultural anthropology (which focus on different facets of culture, such as religion, gender, politics, economics, etc.) and how these facets are linked and integrated in each culture

Students taking this course will:
acquire basic knowledge in medical anthropology;
learn the skills to comprehend the drug history in Hong Kong, China, and other parts of the world;
develop the ability to apply the learned knowledge to analyze the complex relationship between science and culture; and
acquire a critical mind to evaluate any social issues.

By the end of this course, if you have participated, you will be able to:
Understand what constitutes cultural heritage in Hong Kong and how that cultural heritage has developed;
Understand the issues facing built heritage in Hong Kong and the laws and other means intended to safeguard Hong Kong’s built heritage;
Understand the issues facing portable heritage in Hong Kong and the laws and other means intended to safeguard Hong Kong’s portable heritage;
Understand the issues facing water heritage in Hong Kong and the laws and other means intended to safeguard Hong Kong’s water heritage;
Understand the issues facing intangible cultural heritage in Hong Kong and the laws and other means intended to safeguard Hong Kong’s intangible cultural heritage;
Apply your understanding to analyse the issues that may arise in the legal protection of cultural heritage in Hong Kong;
Apply this understanding to evaluate the success of Hong Kong’s current safeguarding measures and consider possible development of the safeguarding framework;
Appreciate the continued importance of cultural heritage to Hong Kong’s success as a world city and how the law may assist in safeguarding cultural heritage in Hong Kong, and promoting it.

After successfully completing this course, the students will be able to:
Evaluate the conflicting views on the reasons for the lack of a more sustainable development;
Analyze where the solutions may lay for SDGs, and the economic, social and environmental constraints to the adoption of these solutions;
Students will be able to understand and describe cognitive, socio-economic and behavioural aspects of sustainable development, and
Comprehend the skills necessary to interpret the policies of governments and international organisations.

By the end of the course, students should be able to:
understand the cultural, social, historical and linguistic development of Hong Kong English in relation to the major conceptual frameworks the course has explored;
critically examine how language attitudes and standard language ideologies develop in different societies, and how gender and identity impact attitudes and ideologies across cultures;
demonstrate an understanding of language attitudes and cultures through original research on the attitudes towards and status of Hong Kong English in Hong Kong society;
define and give examples of different features of Hong Kong English;
conduct original research on either written or spoken features of Hong Kong English;
read and analyze research on Hong Kong English;
use technology to conduct research on Hong Kong English;
become more digitally literate through the reading, analysis, and writing of online Hong Kong English content
.

Subject specific skills.
On successful completion of this course you will:
be able to identify and apply key linguistic and cultural theories;
have accumulated linguistic, historical and cultural knowledge relating to World Englishes in different societies and cultures;
have developed an applied understanding of theoretical frameworks for reading English language cultures generally.
Central academic skills.
On successful completion of this course you will have developed:
analytical skills pertinent to visual and written texts;
organizational skills in the preparation of various writing and presentation assignments;
basic research skills using textual and visual sources;
basic writing skills in standard academic formats (presentations, essays).
Transferable skills.
On successful completion of this course you will have:
become confident in expressing your views, asking questions, and responding to others, even in large groups;
become more professional in delivering formal presentations of your work.

This course will provide a broad intellectual perspective for students and enable them to develop a holistic understanding of environmental and resource management issues related to ecotourism. Students will acquire basic knowledge of ecotourism development and its potential and can be capable of making judgment in response to critical issues on conservation and natural resource management. Since ecotourism, sustainable tourism and sustainable development (including SDGs) are inter-connected concepts in theoretical and practical perspectives, students are expected to incorporate and integrate these areas of knowledge with various cases and examples provided in the course.
Specifically, after successfully completing this course, students will be able to:
- Understand the basic concepts of ecotourism and its relation with the overall tourism industry; especially connecting ecotourism with sustainable tourism development;
- Acquire knowledge in operating and managing ecotourism activities; and particularly how these ecotourism activities may impact economic, socio-cultural and ecological/environmental sustainability;
- Develop an understanding and the skills and approaches necessary for interpreting relevant policy and planning of natural and man-made resources for (eco)tourism; and
- Enhance problem-solving capability using an integrative approach and critical thinking as introduced in the course, which draws students’ attention to how tourism and ecotourism may contribute to SDGs potentially

After taking this course, students are expected to:
be aware of the environmental variations around the world;
be critical in the pursuit of better, if not ideal, environment for living;
be familiar with the development of city and the process of urbanisation;
develop sustainable urban planning and climate resilience strategies;
appreciate the beauty and aesthetics of various human settlement forms; and
realise that man must best use his environment and natural resource in a sustainable manner

Food is a basic need of human beings and food security is often assumed in an affluent society like Hong Kong. However, world hunger is increasing, and both developed and less developed countries have large numbers of hungry people. After taking this course, students will be able to:
1. Explain different global food and hunger issues in a comprehensive perspective;
2. Distinguish the advantages and disadvantages of different forms of global food production to reduce world hunger and reach zero hunger (SDG2) of sustainable development goals from a historical perspective;
3. Analyze the consequences of different food production programs to meet the needs of a growing population in China from a spatiotemporal perspective;
4. Assess the world capacity of food production to explore sustainable food production for all to achieve Sustainable Development Goals (particularly SDG2 Zero Hunger) in a futuristic perspective.
Parallel to the enhancement of knowledge based on food, hunger and Sustainable Development Goals, students should also be able to further improve their critical thinking and analytical capability through problem-based teaching and learning.

After completing the course, students will be able to:
Know the development and changing status of comics and graphic novels within the wider history of Western Europe and North America;
identify how these changes took place and how they redefined comics and graphic novels in the present;
recognize the main artists of the medium, how they were influenced by their cultural context and how they also influenced it in return;
build informed opinion on the quality and relevance of the comics of the 20
th
and 21
st
century.
Develop skills in writing academic essays and speaking in public.

Upon successful completion of this course, students should be able to:
1. Describe the evolution of the globalized culture and society and identify how different factors contribute to the formulation and transformation of global culture and society;
2. Understand the basic concepts, theories and analytical approaches in understanding the diversity of different cultural and social systems across the globe;
3. Critically analyze the basic characteristics, process of cultural globalization and its interaction with national, regional and international society;
4. Describe and analyze the roles and functions of state and non-state actors in shaping global culture and society, etc.;
5. Analyze the role and functions of communication, media and technology in the context of the globalized culture and society; and
6. Critically reflect the role and impacts of global capitalism on cultural globalization;
If possible, seminar by invited guest will be arranged to provide students with insights into the debates and controversies in contemporary world economy.

After completing the course, students will be able to:
- understand the development of visual and material cultures of the Ming dynasty
- explain the production technologies and visual characteristics of representative artworks and artefacts of the Ming dynasty;
- analyze different factors contributing to a social phenomenon related to images and objects in China;
- analyze and evaluate evidence and argument of academic papers;
- apply course knowledge and research methods to compose an academic essay.

1. Be able to understand the economic, socio-cultural, and political background of contemporary China;
2. Be able to apply theories of globalization and popular culture on issues of contemporary China;
3. Be able to analyse culture phenomena in contemporary China;
4. Develop reading, writing, and presentation skills in a professional manner.

After taking this course, students will be able to:
(1) describe and explain the roles of Internet in the formation of the contemporary society and how it leads to social change;
(2) discuss various social and cultural phenomena in relation to the development of Internet;
(3) evaluate different claims about the impact of communication technologies in information society;
(4) identify and analyze core debates about Internet, digital media and information society; and
(5) become an informed and ethical user in the new media environment.

Upon the completion of this course, students should be able to:
1. comprehend the meaning and nature of economic insecurity in globalized world;
2. understand the extent of economic insecurity and poverty in Hong Kong and in other societies;
3. acquire knowledge on social security as a societal measure to combat economic insecurity and poverty;
4. become familiar with the political and economic contexts in the development of social security, national differences in the provision of economic security, major types of provisions and issues of social security;
5. analyze contemporary debates regarding the philosophy and future direction of social security development in national and cross-national perspective.

Upon successful completion of this course, students are expected to acquire the following outcomes:
Remembering:
• The characteristics of an organizational crisis;
• The types of crisis in modern societies;
Understanding
• A full understanding of the consequence a crisis can have on the reputation and
success of businesses and organizations;
Analyzing and applying
• Ability to identify key messages, formulate appropriate responses and utilize
practical techniques to communicate with stakeholders about crisis situations;
• Skills necessary to address the issues when a crisis situation demands immediate
public response;
• Understanding of the dynamics and implications of various public relations
strategies;
• Mastery of relevant theories, as well as practical techniques and planning
necessary to successfully communicate before, during and after a crisis situation.
• Understanding how the Internet has facilitated the rising collective power of
consumers and commercial democracy in modern societies.
Synthesizing and creating
· Creating effective crisis communication plans to handle crises;
· Utilizing the social media platform to restore corporate image and reputation in the post-crisis stage.

After the completion of this course, students will:
Understand and appreciate the cultural dimensions of business operations and organization in different historical, political, and social settings;
Acquire the necessary ethnographic skills to study diverse aspects of business operations and organization;
Be able to rethink and challenge the existing assumptions regarding business practices in the modern world;
Gain the analytical tools to examine issues of over-consumption, over-production, dispossession, oppression, and other relevant discontent under global capitalism;
Be able to examine critically the role SDGs could play in addressing disparities and injustices in the world;
Understand the importance of building a more inclusive, equal and diverse society.

Students who have taken this course will:
be able to see and understand the cultural and historical nature of sports;
understand the roles that sports play in modern societies;
know how to apply fieldwork methods to research a group’s sub-culture, including implicit and explicit rules;
be able to analyze the elements of competition, cooperation, luck and skill, and other variables that make sports entertaining to play and watch and talk about;
be able to analyze and appreciate other sports that they will encounter later in life.

Understand the main concepts related to the processes of global economic/social/political integration, such as regionalism, global governance, interdependence;
Be exposed to the main controversies resulted from globalization processes, e.g., trade liberalization and the 'race to the bottom', human rights and
sovereignty, global market forces and the goal of nature conservation, and
democratic deficit in global institutions;
- -Have the ability to form independent idea about the causes, impact and controversies of globalization by applying the key concepts covered in the course;
Have the ability to related the macro-level factors of globalization to current affairs in Hong Kong society.

Upon completion of this course, students will be able to:
1. Acquire knowledge of the key concepts and theoretical perspectives of multiculturalism, related social policies and service delivery system;
2. Apply an intercultural perspective to understand the struggles, challenges and socio-cultural barriers of ethnic groups in Hong Kong.
3. Evaluate the impact of culture on individuals and/or groups’ values, beliefs, behaviours, attitudes, preferences and life pursuits;
4. Develop awareness in cultural sensitivity and acquire cultural competence as well as intercultural intelligence

Upon completion of this course, students will be able to
· Realise how social innovations work to target social issues, creating social values through innovative strategies in various sectors as well as cross sectoral collaboration;
· Recognize the basic know-hows of social innovation such as design thinking, community or civic engagement, collaboration, prototyping and lean start-up;
· Apprehend how social innovation leverage their work and impact to catalyze changes in the broader community, economy or political sphere.
· Critically evaluate how social innovation can fulfil the objectives of coping with the challenges in the social, economic, cultural and political spheres.
· Acquire personal experience and prepare to taking own responsibilities as global citizen and ready to be social innovator / social entrepreneur in tackling the local, regional and global development challenges.

Upon completion of this course, students will be able to
· Understand how social entrepreneurs work to blend disparate goals, how and why social enterprises successfully fuse purpose and personal passion in business, and how visions and values are embedded in organizational culture;
· Be familiar with a variety of approaches and tools to measure organizational performance and social impact of social enterprise.
· Examine the key methods, strategies and models for social enterprises to succeed;
· Understand the dimensions and models of social entrepreneurship and the strategies on fundraising, financial management, opportunity seeking, social marketing, alliance building, etc.
· Apprehend how social enterprises leverage their work and impact to influence policy and the community;
Critically evaluate how social enterprise can fulfil the objectives of meeting economic, ecological and social needs.

At the end of this course, students will be able to:
understand the complexity of environmental issues as an interplay between science, politics, values, economy, education and social development;
critically understand key environmental issues at both local and global levels;
actively participate in the discourse and actions concerning environmental issues;
recognize different approaches to environmental education and critically analyze their strengths and constraints;
understand the relations between environmental education and cultural differences;
actively participate in environmental education both inside and outside the school systems;
appreciate and to live an environmentally-friendly lifestyle

Upon completion of the course, students will be able to:
cite the major arguments in the current philosophical debates over the social and moral status of nonhuman animals, and understand the strengths and weakness of each;
recount the historical, scientific and cultural contexts of the debate;
discuss the broad range of animal exploitation and the moral issues that each form of it raises;
form a conclusion about the ethics of using animals and defend it with a strong, logical argument.
appreciate and enrich our emotional connection with animal (SDG#3 Good Health and Well-Being).
deepen our understand towards ourselves and different species on earth (SDG#14 Life below water & SDG#15 Life on land).
envision for a just society in which all species could co-exist peacefully (SDG#16 Peace, Justice and Strong institutions).

Explain the relationships between money, land and housing;
Understand factors determining land and housing prices;
Identify the effects of housing price fluctuations on financial stability and wealth inequality;
Appreciate the effect of monetary and land policies on housing affordability;
Draw implications from the owner-renter dichotomy on the housing policy; and
Analyse the sustainability issues of public housing and cooperative housing systems.

(1) To explain the historical, economic and geopolitical background of the Belt and Road Initiative;
(2) To analyze economic, social, environmental, cultural and political forces, structures and processes associated with the Belt and Road Initiative;
(3) To evaluate the built environment and urban issues of Eurasian cities and how these may be improved by appropriate integration into the Belt and Road infrastructure;
(4) To apply Hong Kong’s world-class urban management practices to help the Belt and Road countries to maximize the benefits of network externality effects;
(5) To simulate and predict multi-scale spatial economic and urban outcomes of the Belt and Road infrastructure investments.
(6) To synthesize intercultural and global perspectives and to recommend ways to foster international cooperation, cultural diversity and integration.

Students are expected to achieve the following learning outcomes:
Discuss the social factors that influence language use;
Identify the key issues in sociolinguistics and discuss these issues using the appropriate terminology;
Identify common sociolinguistic phenomena in daily communication settings;
Conduct basic analysis of sociolinguistic phenomena using the concepts learned in the course.

1. Understand how humans have engaged the environment historically and cross-culturally;
2. Examine the relationship between the environment, local communities and the state in the present world through issues including deforestation, climate change, and nuclear disaster;
3. Explore contemporary environmental crises to cultivate sensitivity to possible forms of resistance and action from local and global perspectives.

Students taking this course will:

learn to see the cultural nature of reality and of the supernatural;

understand how many apparently irrational and bizarre beliefs make sense in their cultural contexts;

learn how to use critical thinking while at the same time being tolerant of other views;

develop a healthy scientific skepticism, while at the same time remaining open to new ideas;

be able to analyze other cases that will emerge later in life.

Upon completing this course, students will be able to:
analyze the globalization of culture, a process taking place across the world today and shaping all of our lives;
recognize different aspects of the globalization of culture, including those involving recent history, economics, consumption, mass media, migration, and cultural identity;
discuss the costs and benefits of contemporary processes of globalization to individuals, societies, and the world; and
evaluate the nature of your own culture and selves within a globalizing world.

Upon completion of the course, students will be able to
1. describe how minorities are historically, socially and economically constructed and their lived experiences;
2. understand and identify issues pertinent to multifarious minorities in Hong Kong with political economy, feminist, critical race theory phenomenological and queer approaches;
3. identify and analyse in what way power relations are established and resisted in the construction of minorities and the social as well as institutional responses to them in the form of public policy.
4. increase awareness of SDGs, particularly the relevance of public policy to the attainment of these goals

Upon completion of the course, students should be able to:
1. 
state the key issues and concepts in the field of men’s and masculinities studies;
2. 
distinguish the competing theoretical approaches to men and masculinities;
3. 
understand men and masculinities in a cross-cultural perspective;
4. 
recognize that social class, sexuality, race/ethnicity and age cut across the issues pertinent to men’s and masculinities studies;
5. 
comment on the strengths and weaknesses of various theoretical approaches to men and masculinities;
6. 
theorize contemporary social issues in relation to men and masculinities;
7. critically engage with inequality in society in relation to different modes and notions of masculinities.

By completing the course, the students will:
Gain proficiency in analyzing an individual work of painting, sculpture, architecture, ceramic, and other high-end craft;
Comprehend overall geography and political history of Korea;
Reconsider the construct of “Korean” identity in its pre-modern, colonial, and post-colonial discourses;
Be enabled to think critically the process of Sinicization (i.e. the repercussions of Chinese culture in local context); and
Develop skills in participating in scholarly arguments and writing an academic essay.

By completing the course, the students will:
Gain proficiency in analyzing individual works of painting, sculpture, architecture, ceramic, and other high-end craft;
Comprehend overall geography, literature, and political and religious history of Japan;
Reconsider the construct of “Japanese” identity in various historical and cultural discourses;
Be enabled to think critically about the process of cultural contact (mainly with China, Korea, and the West); and
Develop skills in participating in scholarly arguments and writing an academic essay.

Learning Outcomes:
On successful completion of the course, students are expected to be able to:
Explain the concern of other-than-human animal with cultural studies perspective;
Identify the key issues and critical assessment of human-animal relationship;
Understand the approach in studying culture, animal and environment;
Enrich the angle of analyzing human living and animal species.

At the end of this class students are expected to be able to:
(1) understand major issues of global orders and global governance;
(2) discuss them in the historical context in which they were developed;
(3) identify their contributions to thinking and methods in global society;
(4) trace how concepts have evolved through historical circumstances, theoretical debates, and methodological innovations;
(5) recognize the major theoretical and policy challenges of global governance, social problems and globalization;
(6) prepare for further understanding of relevant themes and debates in the public and private sectors, including but not limited to such emerging fields as ESG investment, ESG reporting, carbon trading, and carbon neutral policy in Hong Kong and Mainland China.
